Summary

the following document generates a capabilities index using data from the RuWell project in the Balkan countries of Albania, Moldova, Kosovo, and Romania. It is a multidimensional index that predicts potential capability using a Bayesian graded response model estimated using the brms package. Factor analyses are used to determine the multidimensional structure of the data, and to select the items. After fitting the model, the fit is assessed using a k-folds cross-validation test, as well as a set of posterior predictive checks. Following the tests, overall model results are generated, then the latent traits (dimension-specific capabilities) are extracted and used in a series of auxiliary regressions.

d <- read_dta("ruwell-final-wide.dta")

Preparing the data for CFA

Creating an object of the variables going into the model

y_vars <- paste0("y", 1:38)

Converting specified variables to ordered factors

for (var in y_vars) {
  d[[var]] <- factor(d[[var]], levels = sort(unique(d[[var]])), ordered = TRUE)
}

Sub-setting the data to include only the variables of interest

vars <- d[, y_vars]

Setting row and column names for the polychoric correlation matrix

rownames(polychoric_corr) <- y_vars
colnames(polychoric_corr) <- y_vars

Fitting the CFA model

Defining the model

cfa_model <- '
  social =~ y1 + y35 + y37 + y38
  personal =~ y6 + y9 + y12 + y24 + y27
  environmental =~ y20 + y21 + y22
  
  social =~ y24
  social =~ y6
  social =~ y22
  personal =~ y20
'

Fitting the model using the polychoric correlation matrix

fit1 <- cfa(cfa_model, sample.cov = polychoric_corr, sample.nobs = nrow(d))

Cross-validation test

Setting seed and selecting a 70% sample for training data

set.seed(3905)                               
n <- nrow(d)  
train <- sample(1:n, size = round(0.7 * n))

Splitting the data into training and validation sets

d_train <- d[train, ]
d_validate <- d[-train, ]

Fitting the model on the training data

fit_train <- cfa(cfa_model, 
                 data = d_train, 
                 estimator = "WLSMV",  
                 ordered = TRUE)

Fitting the model on the validation data

fit_validation <- cfa(cfa_model, 
                      data = d_validate, 
                      estimator = "WLSMV", 
                      ordered = TRUE, 
                      mimic = "lavaan")

dimension_mapping <- tibble(
  original_item = c(
    "y1", "y35", "y37", "y38",          # Social
    "y6", "y9", "y12", "y24", "y27",    # Personal
    "y20", "y21", "y22"                 # Environmental
  ),

    rep(2, 5),  
    rep(3, 3)
  )
)

The next block of code performs the following primary functions: 1. Drops variables that are not used for the models 2. Specifies response variables as numeric 3. Renumbers response variables to be consecutive 4. Generates a variable item

d <- d %>%
  select(id, all_of(covariates), all_of(vars_keep)) %>%
  pivot_longer(
    cols = all_of(vars_keep),         # Specify the columns to pivot
    names_to = "original_item",       # Track original item name
    values_to = "y"                   # Response variable
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    y = as.numeric(y),                # Remove labels from `y`
    item = dense_rank(original_item)  # Renumber items consecutively
  ) %>%
  left_join(dimension_mapping, by = "original_item") %>%
  mutate(
    y = as.ordered(y),
    item = as.factor(item),           # Convert `item` to factor
    dimension = as.factor(dimension)  # Convert `dimension` to factor
  ) %>%
  arrange(id, item)                   # Ensure proper order

Graded response model (the capabilities index)

Specifying the model with a country fixed effect, a random effects parameter that allows for freely-estimated covariances among the dimensions, and an item-specific discrimination parameter

formula1 <- bf(
  y ~ 1 + country +                                # Country fixed effect 
    (1 + dimension | item) + (0 + dimension | id), # Random effects terms
  disc ~ 1 + (1 | item)                            # Discrimination parameter
)

Specifying the priors. Broad weakly informative priors are used so the data dominates the posterior estimates. These can be tightened further if the postestimation tests detect weak predictive performance.

prior1 <- 
  prior(lkj(1), class = "cor") +
  prior(normal(0, 5), class = "sd") +
  prior(normal(0, 5), class = "b") +
  prior(normal(0, 5), class = "Intercept") +
  prior(normal(0, 1), class = "Intercept", dpar = "disc")

Postestimation testing

The following section conducts all postestimation testing. The tests include a k-folds cross-validation test using 4 folds with the data parsed randomly by country, and three posterior predictive checks.

K-folds test

The next block of code is an ifelse function that first checks if the test has already been conducted and saved. If so, it skips the testing function to save computation time.

if (file.exists("fold_test.rds")) {
  message("Results file found.")
  folds <- readRDS("fold_test.rds")
} else {
  message("Running k-fold test. Sit back and relax...")
  
  # Extracting the exact data used in the model
  d_model <- fit2$data
  message("Using model data with ", nrow(d_model), " observations")
  
  # Assigning stratified individual-level folds 
  individuals <- d_model %>%
    select(id, country) %>%
    distinct()
  
  fold_assignment <- individuals %>%
    group_by(country) %>%
    mutate(fold = sample(rep(1:4, length.out = n()))) %>%
    ungroup() %>%
    select(id, fold)
  
  d_model <- d_model %>% 
    left_join(fold_assignment, by = "id")
  
  fold_vector <- d_model$fold
  message("Length of fold vector: ", length(fold_vector))
  
  # Running test in parallel sessions 
  plan(multisession, workers = 4)
  folds <- kfold(fit2, folds = fold_vector, chains = 1, save_fits = T)
  plan(sequential)
  
  saveRDS(folds, "fold_test.rds")
  message("Results saved to dat folder")
}

Auxiliary regressions (latent trait models)

Data prep

Extracting the latent traits into a second data set

d2 <- d %>%
  select(id, all_of(covariates)) %>%
  distinct() %>%  # Keep only one row per person
  mutate(
    # Dimension-specific random effects
    theta_dim1 = ranef1$id[as.character(id), "Estimate", "dimension1"],
    theta_dim2 = ranef1$id[as.character(id), "Estimate", "dimension2"], 
    theta_dim3 = ranef1$id[as.character(id), "Estimate", "dimension3"],
    # Standard errors
    se_dim1 = ranef1$id[as.character(id), "Est.Error", "dimension1"],
    se_dim2 = ranef1$id[as.character(id), "Est.Error", "dimension2"],
    se_dim3 = ranef1$id[as.character(id), "Est.Error", "dimension3"]
  )

Specifying the regression models

Social dimension

formula2 <- bf(
  theta_dim1 | se(se_dim1, sigma = TRUE) ~ 
    country + s(age, by = country, bs = "tp")
)

Personal dimension

formula3 <- bf(
  theta_dim2 | se(se_dim2, sigma = TRUE) ~ 
    country + s(age, by = country, bs = "tp")
)

Environmental dimension

formula4 <- bf(
  theta_dim3 | se(se_dim3, sigma = TRUE) ~ 
    country + s(age, by = country, bs = "tp")
)

Setting weakly informative priors. This function will work for all three auxiliary regressions.

prior2 <- c(
  prior(normal(0, 5), class = "b"),
  prior(normal(0, 5), class = "sds"),
  prior(normal(0, 5), class = "Intercept"),
  prior(normal(0, 5), class = "sigma")
)

Fitting the models

Social model

fit3 <- brm(
  formula = formula2,
  data = d2,
  family = brmsfamily("gaussian"),
  prior = prior2,
  chains = 4,
  iter = 4000,
  warmup = 2000,
  control = list(adapt_delta = 0.99),
  cores = parallel::detectCores(),
  file = "01-ruwell-FINAL2.rds"
)
